*Let $`V` be a finite dimensional vector space.*

_Hint._ Use the fact that the infinite chain of subspaces

$$`\operatorname{ker} T \subseteq \operatorname{ker} T^2 \subseteq \operatorname{ker} T^3 \subseteq \dots`

and the similar chain for $`\operatorname{img} T` must eventually stabilize
(for dimension reasons).

_Solution._ Consider

$$`\{0\} \subsetneq \operatorname{ker} S \subseteq \operatorname{ker} S^2 \subseteq \operatorname{ker} S^3 \subseteq \dots and V \supsetneq \operatorname{img} S \supseteq \operatorname{img} S^2 \supseteq \operatorname{img} S^3 \supseteq \dots.`

For dimension reasons, these subspaces must eventually stabilize:
for some large integer $`N`,
$`\operatorname{ker} T^N = \operatorname{ker} T^{N+1} = \dots`
and $`\operatorname{img} T^N = \operatorname{img} T^{N+1} = \operatorname{img} T^{N+2} = \dots`.
When this happens, $`\operatorname{ker} T^N \bigcap \operatorname{img} T^N = \{0\}`,
since $`T^N` is an automorphism of $`\operatorname{img} T^N`.
On the other hand, by Rank-Nullity we also have
$`\dim \operatorname{ker} T^N + \dim \operatorname{img} T^n = \dim V`.
Thus for dimension reasons, $`V = \operatorname{ker} T^N \oplus \operatorname{img} T^N`.


