*Putnam 2015.*

_Hint._ There is a family of solutions other than just $`a=b=c=d`.

One can solve the problem using Cayley-Hamilton.
A more \`\`bare-hands" approach is to
show the matrix is invertible (unless $`a=b=c=d`)
and then diagonalize the matrix as
$`M = \begin{bmatrix} s & -q \\ -r & p \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 & 0 \\ 0 & \lambda_2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} p & q \\ r & s \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} ps\lambda_1 - qr\lambda_2 & qs(\lambda_1-\lambda_2) \\ pr(\lambda_2-\lambda_1) & ps\lambda_2 - qr\lambda_1 \end{bmatrix}`.

_Solution._ The answer is

$$`\begin{bmatrix} t&t\\t&t \end{bmatrix} \quad\text{and}\quad \begin{bmatrix} -3t&-t\\t&3t \end{bmatrix}`

for $`t \in \mathbb{R}`.
These work by taking $`k=3`.

Now to see these are the only ones, consider an arithmetic matrix

$$`M = \begin{bmatrix} a & a+e \\ a+2e & a+3e \end{bmatrix}.`

with $`e \neq 0`.
Its characteristic polynomial is $`t^2 - (2a+3e)t - 2e^2`,
with discriminant $`(2a+3e)^2 + 8e^2`,
so it has two distinct real roots; moreover, since $`-2e^2 \le 0`
either one of the roots is zero or they are of opposite signs.
Now we can diagonalize $`M` by writing

$$`M = \begin{bmatrix} s & -q \\ -r & p \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 & 0 \\ 0 & \lambda_2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} p & q \\ r & s \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} ps\lambda_1 - qr\lambda_2 & qs(\lambda_1-\lambda_2) \\ pr(\lambda_2-\lambda_1) & ps\lambda_2 - qr\lambda_1 \end{bmatrix}`

where $`ps-qr=1`. By using the fact the diagonal entries have sum equalling
the off-diagonal entries, we obtain that

$$`(ps-qr)(\lambda_1+\lambda_2) = (qs-pr)(\lambda_1-\lambda_2) \implies qs-pr = \frac{\lambda_1+\lambda_2}{\lambda_1-\lambda_2}.`

Now if $`M^k \in S` too then the same calculation gives

$$`qs-pr = \frac{\lambda_1^k+\lambda_2^k}{\lambda_1^k-\lambda_2^k}.`

Let $`x = \lambda_1/\lambda_2 < 0` (since $`-2e^2 < 0`). We appropriately get

$$`\frac{x+1}{x-1} = \frac{x^k+1}{x^k-1} \implies \frac{2}{x-1} = \frac{2}{x^k-1} \implies x = x^k \implies x = -1 or x = 0`

and $`k` odd. If $`x=0` we get $`e=0` and if $`x=-1` we get $`2a+3e=0`,
which gives the curve of solutions that we claimed.

A slicker approach is by Cayley-Hamilton.
Assume that $`e \neq 0`, so $`M` has two distinct real eigenvalues as above.
We have $`M^k = cM + d\operatorname{id}` for some constants $`c` and $`d`
(since $`M` satisfies some quadratic polynomial).
Since $`M \in S`, $`M^k \in S` we obtain $`d=0`.
Thus $`M^k = cM`, so it follows the eigenvalues of $`M` are negatives of each other.
That means $`\operatorname{Tr} M = 0`, and the rest is clear.

*Let $`V` be a finite-dimensional vector space over $`k` and $`T \colon V \to V`.*

_Hint._ Take bases, and do a fairly long calculation.

_Solution._ Pick a basis $`e_1, \dots, e_n` of $`V`.
Let $`T` have matrix $`(x_{ij})`, and let $`m = \dim V`.
Let $`\delta_{ij}` be the Kronecker delta.
Also, let $`\operatorname{Fix}(\sigma)` denote the fixed points of a permutation $`\sigma`
and let $`\operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma)` denote the non-fixed points.

Expanding then gives

$$`\begin{aligned}&\qquad \det (a \cdot \operatorname{id} - T) \\ &= \sum_{\sigma \in S_m} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \cdot \prod_{i=1}^m \left( a \cdot \delta_{i \sigma(i)} - x_{i \sigma(i)} \right)\right) \\ &= \sum_{s=0}^m \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_s \le m} \sum_{\substack{\sigma \in S_m \\ \sigma \text{ fixes } i_k}} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \cdot \prod_{i=1}^m \left( a \cdot \delta_{i \sigma(i)} - x_{i \sigma(i)} \right)\right) \\ &= \sum_{s=0}^m \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_s \le m} \sum_{\substack{\sigma \in S_m \\ \sigma \text{ fixes } (i_k)}} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \cdot \prod_{i \notin (i_k)} -x_{i \sigma(i)} \prod_{i \in (i_k)}^n \left( a \cdot - x_{ii} \right)\right) \\ &= \sum_{\sigma \in S_m} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \cdot \prod_{i \in \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma)} -x_{i \sigma(i)} \prod_{i \in \operatorname{Fix}(\sigma)} \left( a - x_{ii} \right)\right) \\ &= \sum_{\sigma \in S_m} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \cdot \left( \prod_{i \in \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma)} -x_{i \sigma(i)} \right) \left( \sum_{t=0}^{\left\lvert \operatorname{Fix}(\sigma) \right\rvert} a^{\left\lvert \operatorname{Fix}(\sigma) \right\rvert - t} \cdot \sum_{i_1 < \dots < i_t \in \operatorname{Fix}(\sigma)} \prod_{k=1}^t -x_{i_k i_k} \right) \right) \\ &= \sum_{\sigma \in S_m} \left( \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \left( \sum_{t=0}^{\left\lvert \operatorname{Fix}(\sigma) \right\rvert} a^{m-t-\left\lvert \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma) \right\rvert} \sum_{\substack{X \subseteq \{1, \dots, m\} \\ \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma) \subseteq X \\ X \text{ has exactly } t \text{ fixed}}} \prod_{i \in X} -x_{i \sigma(i)} \right) \right) \\ &= \sum_{n=0}^m a^{m-n} \left( \sum_{\sigma \in S_m} \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \sum_{\substack{X \subseteq \{1, \dots, m\} \\ \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma) \subseteq X \\ \left\lvert X \right\rvert = n} } \prod_{i \in X} -x_{i \sigma(i)} \right) \\ &= \sum_{n=0}^m a^{m-n} (-1)^n \left( \sum_{\substack{X \subseteq \{1, \dots, m\} \\ \left\lvert X \right\rvert = n} } \sum_{\substack{\sigma \in S_m \\ \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma) \subseteq X}} \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \prod_{i \in X} x_{i \sigma(i)} \right).\end{aligned}`

Hence it's the same to show that

$$`\sum_{\substack{X \subseteq \{1, \dots, m\} \\ \left\lvert X \right\rvert = n} } \sum_{\substack{\sigma \in S_m \\ \operatorname{NoFix}(\sigma) \subseteq X}} \operatorname{sign}(\sigma) \prod_{i \in X} x_{i \sigma(i)} = \operatorname{Tr}_{\bigwedge^n(V)} \left( \bigwedge^n(T) \right)`

holds for every $`n`.

We can expand the definition of trace as using basis elements as

$$`\begin{aligned}\operatorname{Tr}\left( \bigwedge^n(T) \right) &= \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_n \le m} \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n e_{i_k} \right)^\vee \left( \bigwedge^n(T) \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n e_{i_k} \right) \right) \\ &= \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_n \le m} \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n e_{i_k} \right)^\vee \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n T(e_{i_k}) \right) \\ &= \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_n \le m} \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n e_{i_k} \right)^\vee \left( \bigwedge_{k=1}^n \left( \sum_{j=1}^m x_{i_k j} e_j \right) \right) \\ &= \sum_{1 \le i_1 < \dots < i_n \le m} \sum_{\pi \in S_n} \operatorname{sign}(\pi) \prod_{k=1}^n x_{i_{\pi(k)}k} \\ &= \sum_{\substack{X \subseteq \{1,\dots,m\} \\ \left\lvert X \right\rvert = n}} \sum_{\pi \in S_X} \operatorname{sign}(\pi) \prod_{i \in X} x_{t \pi(t)}\end{aligned}`

Hence it remains to show that the permutations over $`X`
are in bijection with the permutations over $`S_m` which fix $`\{1, \dots, m\} - X`,
which is clear, and moreover, the signs clearly coincide.

