*Fundamental theorem of linear algebra.*

_Hint._ Use an earlier result and it will be immediate
(the four quantities equal the $`k` in the theorem).

_Solution._ By an earlier result,
we may select $`e_1`, \…, $`e_n` a basis of $`V`
and $`f_1`, \…, $`f_m` a basis of $`W`
such that $`T(e_i) = f_i` for $`i \le k`
and $`T(e_i) = 0` for $`i > k`.
Then $`T^\vee(f_i^\vee) = e_i^\vee` for $`i \le k`
and $`T^\vee(f_i^\vee) = 0` for $`i > k`.
All four quantities are above are then equal to $`k`.

*Row rank is column rank.*

_Hint._ This actually is just the previous problem in disguise!
The row rank is $`\dim \operatorname{img} T^\vee`
and the column rank is $`\dim \operatorname{img} T`.

*Polynomial criteria for normality.*

_Hint._ If there is a polynomial, check $`TT^\dagger = T^\dagger T` directly.
If $`T` is normal, diagonalize it.

_Solution._ First, suppose $`T^\ast = p(T)`.
Then $`T^\ast T = p(T) \cdot T = T \cdot p(T) = T T^\ast` and we're done.

Conversely, suppose $`T` is diagonalizable
in a way compatible with the inner form
(OK since $`V` is finite dimensional).
Consider the orthonormal basis.
Then $`T` consists of eigenvalues on the main diagonals
and zeros elsewhere, say

$$`T = \left( \begin{array}{cccc} \lambda_1 & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & \lambda_2 & \dots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \dots & \lambda_n \end{array} \right).`

In that case, we find that for any polynomial $`q` we have

$$`q(T) = \left( \begin{array}{cccc} q(\lambda_1) & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & q(\lambda_2) & \dots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \dots & q(\lambda_n) \end{array} \right).`

and

$$`T^\ast = \left( \begin{array}{cccc} \overline{\lambda_1} & 0 & \dots & 0 \\ 0 & \overline{\lambda_2} & \dots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \dots & \overline{\lambda_n} \end{array} \right).`

So we simply require a polynomial $`q`
such that $`q(\lambda_i) = \overline{\lambda_i}` for every $`i`.
Since there are finitely many $`\lambda_i`,
we can construct such a polynomial using Lagrange interpolation.

